### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler-cli

### Description

According to https://angular.dev/guide/zoneless#onpush-compatible-components
>When a library component is a host for user-components which might use [ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default](https://angular.dev/api/core/ChangeDetectionStrategy#Default), it cannot use OnPush because that would prevent the child component from being refreshed if it is not OnPush compatible and relies on ZoneJS to trigger change detection.

As such, I would expect the angular compiler to validate that a component with ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush cannot render a child component with ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default

For example, given the following two components we should show an error on the `<default-cd>` node in the OnPushComponent template:

```
import { ChangeDetectionStrategy, Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'default-cd',
  template: '<p>default change detection</p>',
})
export class DefaultComponent {}

@Component({
  selector: 'onpush-cd',
  template: '<default-cd>',
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  imports: [DefaultComponent],
})
export class OnPushComponent {}
```

This feature will help users incrementally migrate components in older zone.js based applications to use ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush and eventually enable a zoneless architecture. Such a feature would also support OnPush as the implicit change detection strategy (https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/65485).

### Proposed solution

We should add a new `strictChangeDetection` boolean option to `TypeCheckingOptions` interface to allow users to opt-in to new validation logic. If strictChangeDetection is true, any component using ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush cannot render a child component with ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default. If strictChangeDetection is false or not provided, no change detection strategy validation will be performed.

When the validation is performed, an `ngtsc` error should be shown to the user during compilation and also integrate with the Angular Language Service to show the error during development.

The solution should support validation from source code `@Component` decorator metadata and also partially compiled libraries via the generated typescript definition files.

For example, we should modify `…µ…µComponentDeclaration` to include ChangeDetectionStrategy type information.

```
type …µ…µComponentDeclaration<T, Selector extends String, ExportAs extends string[], InputMap extends {
    [key: string]: string | {
        alias: string | null;
        required: boolean;
    };
}, OutputMap extends {
    [key: string]: string;
}, QueryFields extends string[], NgContentSelectors extends string[], IsStandalone extends boolean = false, HostDirectives = never, IsSignal extends boolean = false, changeDetection extends ChangeDetectionStrategy = ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default> = unknown;
```

### Alternatives considered

This validation could also be performed at runtime with a warning that can be shown to the user in development mode.

If a component using ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush renders a component with ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default the angular runtime should print a warning message to the screen on initial render during development mode. It should do this for each case where a Default component is rendered by an OnPush component and the message should list the name of the OnPush component and the Default component being rendered.

Variables are generated in the pipeline by inserting references to all the symbols within the scope and then later cleaning up the unused ones in an optimization pass. When generating the scope for listener instructions, we expose all the `@let` declarations in the same view ([see](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/packages/compiler/src/template/pipeline/src/phases/generate_variables.ts#L293)) which leads us to generate `…µ…µrestoreView` and `…µ…µresetView` calls, however if the `@let` reference isn't used within the listener, the variable optimization phase only removes the variable that reads it and not the `…µ…µrestoreView`/`…µ…µresetView` calls.

For example, if we take the following template:

```html
@let unused = 1;
<button (click)="noop()"></button>
```

It produces the following code before optimization:

```js
if (rf & 1) {
  const _r1 = …µ…µgetCurrentView();
  …µ…µdeclareLet(0);
  …µ…µdomElementStart(1, "button", 0);
  …µ…µdomListener(
    "click",
    function TestComp_Template_button_click_1_listener() {
      const ctx_r1 = …µ…µrestoreView(_r1);
      const unused_r3 = …µ…µreadContextLet(0);
      return …µ…µresetView(ctx.noop());
    }
  );
  …µ…µdomElementEnd();
}
if (rf & 2) {
  const unused_r4 = …µ…µstoreLet(1);
}
```

Which becomes the following after optimization:

```js
if (rf & 1) {
  const _r1 = …µ…µgetCurrentView();
  …µ…µdomElementStart(0, "button", 0);
  …µ…µdomListener(
    "click",
    function TestComp_Template_button_click_0_listener() {
      …µ…µrestoreView(_r1);
      return …µ…µresetView(ctx.noop());
    }
  );
  …µ…µdomElementEnd();
}
if (rf & 2) {
  1;
}
```

The `…µ…µrestoreView` and `…µ…µresetView` calls aren't necessary and should be removed, because there aren't any reads of the unused `@let`.
